## 6. Penetration Testing vs Vulnerability Scanning (Important Distinction)

| Aspect | Vulnerability Scanning | Penetration Testing |
|---|---|---|
| Depth | Automated, surface-level identification | Manual + automated, attempts actual exploitation |
| Goal | Find known weaknesses | Prove real-world impact/exploitability |
| Frequency | Often continuous/scheduled | Periodic (e.g., annually or per compliance requirement) |
| Output | List of vulnerabilities with severity | Narrative report showing attack paths and business impact |

---

## 7. Why This Chapter Is Central to Ethical Hacking

- This chapter is essentially **the job description of a penetration tester/security analyst**: find vulnerabilities, understand their real impact, and recommend/implement fixes.
- Every earlier chapter (devices, protocols, wireless, IoT) feeds into the vulnerability categories here — this is where all prior knowledge is applied practically.
- Compliance frameworks (PCI-DSS, HIPAA, ISO 27001, NIST) all require exactly this cycle: identify vulnerabilities, remediate, verify, repeat.

---

## Quick Revision Points
- Vulnerabilities threaten Confidentiality, Integrity, or Availability (the CIA Triad).
- Categories: configuration, protocol, software/firmware, human/process, physical.
- Vulnerability management lifecycle: Identify → Assess → Remediate → Verify → Monitor.
- Defense-in-depth = layered controls across perimeter, network, endpoint, application, data, identity, and monitoring.
- Zero Trust ("never trust, always verify") is the modern security model replacing pure perimeter-based defense.
- Vulnerability scanning finds weaknesses; penetration testing proves real-world exploitability and impact.
